# Enterprise Service Conventions

All enterprise code lives in `src/enterprise/`. Follow these patterns for consistency.

## Service structure

```typescript
// 1. Injectable with providedIn: 'root' or provided in enterprise-main.ts
@Injectable()
export class EnterpriseSessionService extends SessionService {
  // Extend the upstream abstract class
  // Add auth headers, tenant scoping, etc.
}
```

## Overriding upstream services

When replacing an upstream service, use the same injection token:

```typescript
// enterprise-main.ts
import { SESSION_SERVICE } from '../app/core/services/interfaces/session';
import { EnterpriseSessionService } from './auth/enterprise-session.service';

{ provide: SESSION_SERVICE, useClass: EnterpriseSessionService }
```

## Adding new enterprise-only services

For services that don't replace upstream functionality:

1. Create an interface and injection token in the same file
2. Provide a mock for testing
3. Wire in `enterprise-main.ts`

## State management

- Use Angular signals for synchronous reactive state
- Use RxJS observables for async data flows
- No NgRx — keep it simple, consistent with upstream patterns
